nearEnds

public RrPolygonList nearEnds(Rr2Point startNearHere)
Re-order and (if need be) reverse the order of the polygons in a list so the end of the first is near the start of the second and so on. This is a heuristic - it does not do a full traveling salesman... This deals with both open and closed polygons, but it does not allow closed ones to be re-ordered, even if that would give a shorter path.

Returns:
new ordered polygon list

cutPolygon

private void cutPolygon(int pol,
                        int st,
                        int en)
Remove polygon pol from the list, replacing it with two polygons, the first being pol's vertices from 0 to st inclusive, and the second being pol's vertices from en to its end inclusive. It is permissible for st == en, but if st > en, then they are swapped. The two new polygons are put on the end of the list.

Parameters:
pol -
st -

middleStarts

public void middleStarts(RrPolygonList hatching,
                         LayerRules lc)
This assumes that the RrPolygonList for which it is called is all the outline polygons, and that hatching is their infill hatch. It goes through the outlines and the hatch modifying both so that that outlines actually start and end half-way along a hatch line (that half of the hatch line being deleted). When the outlines are then printed, they start and end in the middle of a solid area, thus minimising dribble. The outline polygons are re-ordered before the start so that their first point is the most extreme one in the current hatch direction.

Parameters:
hatching -
lc -
